{"title_page": "Abergavenny Town F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Abergavenny Town\n| image = \n| fullname = Abergavenny Town Football Club\n| nickname = ''The Pennies'',<br>''The Butchers''\n| founded = 2014\n| ground = Pen-Y-Pound Stadium\n| capacity = \n| owner = \n| chairman = Rob Francis\n| manager = Ben Murphy\n| league = [[Welsh Football League Division One]]\n| season = 2018\u201319\n| position = Welsh Football League Division Two, 10th (of 16)\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| leftarm1 = 0000FF\n| body1 = 0000FF\n| rightarm1 = 0000FF\n| shorts1 = 0000FF\n| socks1 = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = FFFFFF\n| socks2 = FFFFFF|\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Abergavenny Town Football Club''' is a Welsh [[association football]] club based in the town of [[Abergavenny]], [[Monmouthshire]], who play in the [[Welsh Football League Division One]]. The club was founded in June 2014 after local side Govilon changed their name,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fchd.info/ABERGATN.HTM |title=Abergavenny Town |publisher=Football Club History Database |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> eleven months after the former club [[Abergavenny Thursdays F.C.|Abergavenny Thursdays]] folded, citing a lack of players as the reason.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/10623329.Abergavenny_Thursdays_withdraw_from_Gwent_County_League/?ref=rss |title=Abergavenny Thursdays withdraw from Gwent County League |publisher=South Wales Argus |last=Penman |first=Andrew |date=20 August 2013 |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe new club was entered into the [[Gwent County League]] First Division for the 2014-15 season. They finished the season as champions of that division after going the entire league campaign unbeaten . This earned the club a place in the Third Division of the [[Welsh Football League]]. Success continued during the 2015/16 season as the club won promotion to the Second Division after finishing second in the league. The club also won the [[FAW Trophy|FAW trophy]] following a 1-0 victory over Sully Sports. The 2016/17 saw Abergavenny finish 11th in the Second division and the end of the season saw long time servant and Manager Steve \u201cButch\u201d Morgan leave the club after 20 years of involvement at Govillon and Abergavenny. Season 2017/18 saw the club promote reserve team player/manager Ben Bannon to first team manager. Bannon led the team to a 10th place finish in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abergavennytownfc.com/|title=Welcome to the Official Home of Abergavenny Town FC|author=|date=|website=www.abergavennytownfc.com|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pen-Y-Pound Stadium ==\nFootball has been played at Pen-Y-Pound since around the 1930s. Stadium development including building a 250 seat stand and club house were to achieved by Thursday's first management committee led by local businessman Vince Sullivan. Unfortunately the stand hasn't been used since the League of Wales days in the early 1990s but the club are try to get the stand reopened and used in the future.\n\nIn 1963 Pen-Y-Pound was used a helicopter landing site for John Lennon. The Beatles were playing in the Town and Lennon had been in London making an appearance on the BBC television show Juke Box Jury. He landed in Abergavenny's Penypound football ground at 9.50pm, and was driven straight to the Town Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatlesbible.com/1963/06/22/live-town-hall-abergavenny/|title=The Beatles Bible - Live: Town Hall, Abergavenny|date=1963-06-22|website=The Beatles Bible|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe ground has hosted a couple of Welsh Youth international matches during the years.\n\n==Honours==\n*[[Gwent County League]] Division 1 Champions \u2013 2014\u201315<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abergavennytown.co.uk/a/history-51335.html |title=History |publisher=Abergavenny Town F.C. |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Welsh Football League Division Three|Welsh Football League Division 3]] Runners Up - 2015-16\n*[[FAW Trophy]] Winners - 2015-15\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://twitter.com/AbergavennyTFC Official Club Twitter]\n\n{{Welsh Football League Division One teamlist}}\n{{Football in Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Wales]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Sport in Monmouthshire]]\n[[Category:Abergavenny]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Welsh Football League clubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Abergavenny Town\n| image = \n| fullname = Abergavenny Town Football Club\n| nickname = ''The Pennies'',<br>''The Butchers''\n| founded = 2014\n| ground = Pen-Y-Pound Stadium\n| capacity = \n| owner = \n| chairman = Rob Francis\n| manager = Ben Murphy\n| league = [[Welsh Football League Division One]]\n| season = 2018\u201319\n| position = Welsh Football League Division Two, 10th (of 16)\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = \n| pattern_ra1 = \n| leftarm1 = 0000FF\n| body1 = 0000FF\n| rightarm1 = 0000FF\n| shorts1 = 0000FF\n| socks1 = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = FFFFFF\n| socks2 = FFFFFF|\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Abergavenny Town Football Club''' is a Welsh [[association football]] club based in the town of [[Abergavenny]], [[Monmouthshire]], who play in the [[Welsh Football League Division One]]. The club was founded in June 2014 after local side Govilon changed their name,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fchd.info/ABERGATN.HTM |title=Abergavenny Town |publisher=Football Club History Database |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> eleven months after the former club [[Abergavenny Thursdays F.C.|Abergavenny Thursdays]] folded, citing a lack of players as the reason.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/10623329.Abergavenny_Thursdays_withdraw_from_Gwent_County_League/?ref=rss |title=Abergavenny Thursdays withdraw from Gwent County League |publisher=South Wales Argus |last=Penman |first=Andrew |date=20 August 2013 |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe new club was entered into the [[Gwent County League]] First Division for the 2014-15 season. They finished the season as champions of that division after going the entire league campaign unbeaten . This earned the club a place in the Third Division of the [[Welsh Football League]]. Success continued during the 2015/16 season as the club won promotion to the Second Division after finishing second in the league. The club also won the [[FAW Trophy|FAW trophy]] following a 1-0 victory over Sully Sports. The 2016/17 saw Abergavenny finish 11th in the Second division and the end of the season saw long time servant and Manager Steve \u201cButch\u201d Morgan leave the club after 20 years of involvement at Govillon and Abergavenny. Season 2017/18 saw the club promote reserve team player/manager Ben Bannon to first team manager. Bannon led the team to a 10th place finish in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abergavennytownfc.com/|title=Welcome to the Official Home of Abergavenny Town FC|author=|date=|website=www.abergavennytownfc.com|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pen-Y-Pound Stadium ==\nFootball has been played at Pen-Y-Pound since around the 1930's. Stadium development including building a 250 seat stand and club house were to achieved by Thursday's first management committee led by local businessman Vince Sullivan. Unfortunately the stand hasn't been used since the League of Wales days in the early 1990's but the club are try to get the stand reopened and used in the future.\n\nIn 1963 Pen-Y-Pound was used a helicopter landing site for John Lennon. The Beatles were playing in the Town and Lennon had been in London making an appearance on the BBC television show Juke Box Jury. He landed in Abergavenny's Penypound football ground at 9.50pm, and was driven straight to the Town Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatlesbible.com/1963/06/22/live-town-hall-abergavenny/|title=The Beatles Bible - Live: Town Hall, Abergavenny|date=1963-06-22|website=The Beatles Bible|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n\nThe ground has hosted a couple of Welsh Youth international matches during the years.\n\n==Honours==\n*[[Gwent County League]] Division 1 Champions \u2013 2014\u201315<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abergavennytown.co.uk/a/history-51335.html |title=History |publisher=Abergavenny Town F.C. |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Welsh Football League Division Three|Welsh Football League Division 3]] Runners Up - 2015-16\n*[[FAW Trophy]] Winners - 2015-15\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://twitter.com/AbergavennyTFC Official Club Twitter]\n\n{{Welsh Football League Division One teamlist}}\n{{Football in Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Wales]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Sport in Monmouthshire]]\n[[Category:Abergavenny]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Welsh Football League clubs]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abergavenny_Town_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Thomas Jones (footballer, born 1879)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Thomas Jones\n| image                =  \n| fullname             = Thomas Trevellyan Jones\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Outside forward|Outside left]]\n| birth_date          = 1879\n| birth_place = [[Shrewsbury]], England\n| death_date  =\n| years1      = 1898\u2013190? | clubs1 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]]          | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0\n| years2      = 190?\u20131904 | clubs2 = [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]]\n| years3      = 1904\u20131905 | clubs3 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] | caps3 = 2 | goals3 = 0\n| years4      = 1905\u201319?? | clubs4 = [[Shifnal Town F.C.|Shifnal Town]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Trevellyan Jones''' (1879 \u2013 after 1905) was an English [[association football|footballer]] who made two appearances in [[the Football League]] playing for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]].<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData |location=Nottingham |year=2004 |page=143 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref> He played as an [[outside forward|outside left]].\n\nJones was born in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]]. He signed for [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], initially as an [[amateur]], in 1898<ref name=Matthews102>{{cite book |last=Matthews |first=Tony |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |page=102 |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9}}</ref> and spent several years with the club, but never played for them in [[the Football League]].<ref name=Joyce/> A spell with [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] preceded his joining [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] of the [[Football League First Division]] in 1904.<ref name=\"Matthews102\"/> He played three times during the [[1904\u201305 in English football|1904\u201305 season]], twice in the League and once in the [[FA Cup]], as a replacement for [[Oakey Field]], but was out of his depth at that level, and returned to [[non-league football]] with [[Shifnal Town F.C.|Shifnal Town]] in 1905.<ref name=Matthews102/><ref>Matthews, p. 151.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1870s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Thomas Jones\n| image                =  \n| fullname             = Thomas Trevellyan Jones\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Outside forward|Outside left]]\n| birth_date          = 1879\n| birth_place = [[Shrewsbury]], England\n| death_date  =\n| years1      = 1898\u2013190? | clubs1 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]]          | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0\n| years2      = 190?\u20131904 | clubs2 = [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]]\n| years3      = 1904\u20131905 | clubs3 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] | caps3 = 2 | goals3 = 0\n| years4      = 1905\u201319?? | clubs4 = [[Shifnal Town F.C.|Shifnal Town]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Trevellyan Jones''' (1879 \u2013 after 1905) was an English [[association football|footballer]] who made two appearances in [[the Football League]] playing for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]].<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData |location=Nottingham |year=2004 |page=143 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref> He played as an [[outside forward|outside left]].\n\nJones was born in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]]. He signed for [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], initially as an [[amateur]], in 1898<ref name=Matthews102>{{cite book |last=Matthews |first=Tony |title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record |year=1995 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |page=102 |isbn=978-1-85983-010-9}}</ref> and spent several years with the club, but never played for them in [[the Football League]].<ref name=Joyce/> A spell with [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] preceded his joining [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] of the [[Football League First Division]] in 1904.<ref name=\"Matthews102\"/> He played three times during the [[1904\u201305 in English football|1904\u201305 season]], twice in the League and once in the [[FA Cup]], as a replacement for [[Oakey Field]], but was out of his depth at that level, and returned to [[non-league football]] with [[Shifnal Town F.C.|Shifnal Town]] in 1905.<ref name=Matthews102/><ref>Matthews, p. 151.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1870s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Jones_(footballer,_born_1879)"}
{"title_page": "Blackedge whipray", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| name = Blackedge whipray\n| image = Trygon marginatus by annandale.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| status = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{Cite iucn | author = Valenti, S.V. | title = ''Himantura marginata'' | volume = 2009 | page = e.T165290A6000553 | date = 2009 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009.RLTS.T165290A6000553.en }}</ref>\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Chondrichthyes]]\n| subclassis = [[Elasmobranchii]]\n| ordo = [[Myliobatiformes]]\n| familia = [[Dasyatidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Himantura]]''\n| species = '''''H. marginata'''''\n| binomial = ''Himantura marginata''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1860)\n| synonyms = ''Trygon marginatus'' <small>Blyth, 1860</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''blackedge whipray''' (''Himantura marginata'') is a little-known [[species]] of [[Myliobatiformes|stingray]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Dasyatidae]], found in the coastal waters of the [[Bay of Bengal]] and the [[Gulf of Mannar]]. Attaining a disc width of {{convert|1.8|m|ft|abbr=on}}, this species has a diamond-shaped disc with two small concavities on either side of the snout tip, and a long, whip-like tail without tail folds. It is characterized by large thorns with star-shaped bases scattered over the disc, and by the wide, black marginal bands on the underside of the disc. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) currently lacks sufficient data to assess the blackedge whipray beyond [[Data Deficient]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nEnglish [[zoologist]] [[Edward Blyth]] described the blackedge stingray as ''Trygon marginatus'', in an 1860 issue of the ''Journal and Proceedings of the Asiatic Society of Bengal''. Blyth based his account on a specimen {{convert|1.2|m|ft|abbr=on}} across obtained from a fish market in [[Calcutta]], which has since been lost. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''marginatus'' means \"enclosed with a border\" in [[Latin]]. Subsequent authors have placed this species in the genus ''Himantura''.<ref name=\"blyth\">{{cite journal |author=Blyth, E. |date=1860 |title=The cartilaginous fishes of lower Bengal |journal=Journal and Proceedings of the Asiatic Society of Bengal |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=35&ndash;45}}</ref><ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\">{{cite journal |author1=Selvaraj, G.S.D.  |author2=M. Kathirvel  |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Some observations on the ray ''Himantura marginatus'' (Blyth) from the Gulf of Mannar |journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India |date=1980 |volume=22 |issue=1&2 |pages=161&ndash;164}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe blackedge whipray is found off [[Myanmar]],  [[Bengal]] and [[Ganjam]] in [[India]], and in the [[Gulf of Mannar]].<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> Its range may extend as far as [[Indonesia]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/> It is fairly rare compared to other stingrays that share its range.<ref name=\"blyth\"/><ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> This [[benthic fish|bottom-dwelling]] species inhabits coastal waters to at least a depth of {{convert|44|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and sometimes enters [[brackish water]].<ref name=\"fishbase\">{{Fishbase species |genus=Himantura |species=marginatus |month=September |year=2010}}</ref><ref name=\"annandale\">{{cite journal |author=Annandale, N. |date = May 1909|title=Report on the fishes taken by the Bengal fisheries steamer \"Golden Crown.\" Part I, Batoidei |journal=Memoirs of the Indian Museum |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=1&ndash;60}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe [[pectoral fin]] disc of the blackedge whipray is diamond-shaped, wider than long, and thick at the center. The outer corners are narrowly rounded and the leading margins converge at an obtuse angle. The tip of the snout projects slightly, and is flanked by a pair of small, shallow concavities. The eyes are small and followed by larger [[Spiracle (vertebrates)|spiracle]]s. There is a curtain of skin between the nostrils. The mouth is small and bow-shaped, with a papilla (nipple-like structure) near each corner. The numerous teeth are arranged with a [[quincunx]] pattern; each has an oval to [[rhomboid]] base, with a prominent central ridge and low ridges alongside. The [[pelvic fin]]s extend past the disc.<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/><ref name=\"annandale\"/>\n\nThe tail is much longer than the disc and bears a serrated stinging spine on top, about one disc length back from the base. The base of the tail is flattened, tapering to become whip-like past the sting; there are no fin folds. The dorsal surface of the disc is densely covered by granules that become smaller towards the disc margin, starting in front of the disc and reaching the base of the tail. Large thorns with star-shaped bases are found in a row along the midline of the back, as well as scattered over the rest of the disc; these thorns resemble small [[limpet]]s or [[salt crystal]]s, hence the ray's [[Tamil language|Tamil]] name ''uppan thirukai'' (\"salt-like ray\").<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> The tail is smooth up to the spine, and beyond is entirely covered by small granules and prickles. The center of the disc is dark brown or gray above, becoming darker or light violet towards the margins, and sometimes with a posterior yellow area reaching the base of the sting. There may be small yellowish spots scattered over the disc, or a bluish irregular line running around the disc a small distance from the edge. The underside is white with a wide, black, irregularly edged band running along the lateral and posterior disc margins. The tail is brown at the base and white past the sting.<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/><ref name=\"annandale\"/> This large species grows to {{convert|1.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|3.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\n==Biology and ecology==\nVirtually nothing is known of the natural history of the blackedge whipray.<ref name=\"iucn\"/> It is presumably [[aplacental viviparous]] like other members of its family.<ref name=\"fishbase\"/> A known [[parasite]] of this species is the [[tapeworm]] ''Acanthobothrium dighaensis''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Six species of ''Acanthobothrium'' (Eucestoda: Tetraphyllidea) in stingrays (Chondrichthyes: Rajiformes: Myliobatoidei) from Ecuador |author1=Marques, F. |author2=D.R. Brooks |author3=R. Barriga  |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Journal of Parasitology |volume=83 |issue=3 |date=1997 |pages=475&ndash;484 |doi=10.2307/3284414|jstor=3284414 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1236&context=parasitologyfacpubs }}</ref>\n\n==Human interactions==\nThe blackedge whipray is occasionally caught by [[artisan fishing|artisanal]] and [[commercial fishing|commercial fisheries]]. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] does not yet have enough information to assess this species beyond [[Data Deficient]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4548318}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackedge Whipray}}\n[[Category:Himantura]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| name = Blackedge whipray\n| image = Trygon marginatus by annandale.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| status = DD\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{Cite iucn | author = Valenti, S.V. | title = ''Himantura marginata'' | volume = 2009 | page = e.T165290A6000553 | date = 2009 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2009.RLTS.T165290A6000553.en }}</ref>\n| regnum = [[Animalia]]\n| phylum = [[Chordata]]\n| classis = [[Chondrichthyes]]\n| subclassis = [[Elasmobranchii]]\n| ordo = [[Myliobatiformes]]\n| familia = [[Dasyatidae]]\n| genus = ''[[Himantura]]''\n| species = '''''H. marginata'''''\n| binomial = ''Himantura marginata''\n| binomial_authority = ([[Edward Blyth|Blyth]], 1860)\n| synonyms = ''Trygon marginatus'' <small>Blyth, 1860</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''blackedge whipray''' (''Himantura marginata'') is a little-known [[species]] of [[Myliobatiformes|stingray]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Dasyatidae]], found in the coastal waters of the [[Bay of Bengal]] and the [[Gulf of Mannar]]. Attaining a disc width of {{convert|1.8|m|ft|abbr=on}}, this species has a diamond-shaped disc with two small concavities on either side of the snout tip, and a long, whip-like tail without tail folds. It is characterized by large thorns with star-shaped bases scattered over the disc, and by the wide, black marginal bands on the underside of the disc. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) currently lacks sufficient data to assess the blackedge whipray beyond [[Data Deficient]].\n\n==Taxonomy==\nEnglish [[zoologist]] [[Edward Blyth]] described the blackedge stingray as ''Trygon marginatus'', in an 1860 issue of the ''Journal and Proceedings of the Asiatic Society of Bengal''. Blyth based his account on a specimen {{convert|1.2|m|ft|abbr=on}} across obtained from a fish market in [[Calcutta]], which has since been lost. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''marginatus'' means \"enclosed with a border\" in [[Latin]]. Subsequent authors have placed this species in the genus ''Himantura''.<ref name=\"blyth\">{{cite journal |author=Blyth, E. |date=1860 |title=The cartilaginous fishes of lower Bengal |journal=Journal and Proceedings of the Asiatic Society of Bengal |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=35&ndash;45}}</ref><ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\">{{cite journal |author1=Selvaraj, G.S.D.  |author2=M. Kathirvel  |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Some observations on the ray ''Himantura marginatus'' (Blyth) from the Gulf of Mannar |journal=Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India |date=1980 |volume=22 |issue=1&2 |pages=161&ndash;164}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe blackedge whipray is found off [[Myanmar]],  [[Bengal]] and [[Ganjam]] in [[India]], and in the [[Gulf of Mannar]].<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> Its range may extend as far as [[Indonesia]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/> It is fairly rare compared to other stingrays that share its range.<ref name=\"blyth\"/><ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> This [[benthic fish|bottom-dwelling]] species inhabits coastal waters to at least a depth of {{convert|44|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and sometimes enters [[brackish water]].<ref name=\"fishbase\">{{Fishbase species |genus=Himantura |species=marginatus |month=September |year=2010}}</ref><ref name=\"annandale\">{{cite journal |author=Annandale, N. |date = May 1909|title=Report on the fishes taken by the Bengal fisheries steamer \"Golden Crown.\" Part I, Batoidei |journal=Memoirs of the Indian Museum |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=1&ndash;60}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe [[pectoral fin]] disc of the blackedge whipray is diamond-shaped, wider than long, and thick at the center. The outer corners are narrowly rounded and the leading margins converge at an obtuse angle. The tip of the snout projects slightly, and is flanked by a pair of small, shallow concavities. The eyes are small and followed by larger [[Spiracle (vertebrates)|spiracle]]s. There is a curtain of skin between the nostrils. The mouth is small and bow-shaped, with a papilla (nipple-like structure) near each corner. The numerous teeth are arranged with a [[quincunx]] pattern; each has an oval to [[rhomboid]] base, with a prominent central ridge and low ridges alongside. The [[pelvic fin]]s extend past the disc.<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/><ref name=\"annandale\"/>\n\nThe tail is much longer than the disc and bears a serrated stinging spine on atop, about one disc length back from the base. The base of the tail is flattened, tapering to become whip-like past the sting; there are no fin folds. The dorsal surface of the disc is densely covered by granules that become smaller towards the disc margin, starting in front of the disc and reaching the base of the tail. Large thorns with star-shaped bases are found in a row along the midline of the back, as well as scattered over the rest of the disc; these thorns resemble small [[limpet]]s or [[salt crystal]]s, hence the ray's [[Tamil language|Tamil]] name ''uppan thirukai'' (\"salt-like ray\").<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/> The tail is smooth up to the spine, and beyond is entirely covered by small granules and prickles. The center of the disc is dark brown or gray above, becoming darker or light violet towards the margins, and sometimes with a posterior yellow area reaching the base of the sting. There may be small yellowish spots scattered over the disc, or a bluish irregular line running around the disc a small distance from the edge. The underside is white with a wide, black, irregularly edged band running along the lateral and posterior disc margins. The tail is brown at the base and white past the sting.<ref name=\"selvaraj and kathirvel\"/><ref name=\"annandale\"/> This large species grows to {{convert|1.8|m|ft|abbr=on}} across and {{convert|3.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long.<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\n==Biology and ecology==\nVirtually nothing is known of the natural history of the blackedge whipray.<ref name=\"iucn\"/> It is presumably [[aplacental viviparous]] like other members of its family.<ref name=\"fishbase\"/> A known [[parasite]] of this species is the [[tapeworm]] ''Acanthobothrium dighaensis''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Six species of ''Acanthobothrium'' (Eucestoda: Tetraphyllidea) in stingrays (Chondrichthyes: Rajiformes: Myliobatoidei) from Ecuador |author1=Marques, F. |author2=D.R. Brooks |author3=R. Barriga  |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Journal of Parasitology |volume=83 |issue=3 |date=1997 |pages=475&ndash;484 |doi=10.2307/3284414|jstor=3284414 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1236&context=parasitologyfacpubs }}</ref>\n\n==Human interactions==\nThe blackedge whipray is occasionally caught by [[artisan fishing|artisanal]] and [[commercial fishing|commercial fisheries]]. The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] does not yet have enough information to assess this species beyond [[Data Deficient]].<ref name=\"iucn\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4548318}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackedge Whipray}}\n[[Category:Himantura]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blackedge_whipray"}
{"title_page": "Thomas John Thomas", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Thomas Thomas\n|image          =\n| image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|fullname       =  Thomas John Thomas\n|birth_date     = 1877\n|birth_place    = Wales\n|death_date     = <!--{{death date and age|||||||df=yes}}-->\n|death_place    =\n|height         =\n|position       =\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         =\n|clubs1         =\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         =\n|clubs2         =\n|caps2          =\n|goals2         =\n|totalcaps      =\n|totalgoals     =\n|nationalyears1 = 1898\n|nationalteam1  = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  =\n| managerclubs1  =\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Thomas John Thomas''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 1877) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] international [[association football|footballer]]. He was part of the [[Wales national football team]], playing 2 matches. He played his first match on 19 February 1898 against Ireland and his last match on 19 March 1898 against Scotland .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_players.php?id=218|title=Wales player database 1872 to 2013|publisher=eu-football.info|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe studied at the [[Friars School, Bangor]].<ref name=\"Bangor FC\">{{Cite web | url = http://homepages.tesco.net/~BCSA/History/Welshints.htm | title = Welsh International Caps | accessdate = 16 November 2008 | author = History of Bangor City Football Club website | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090203125130/http://homepages.tesco.net/~BCSA/History/Welshints.htm | archivedate = 3 February 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.iffhs.de/?29da15a85b1529d815a89ad5285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec28d6edb0ae1d | title = Welsh Cup 1895/96 | accessdate = 16 November 2008 | author = IFFHS}}</ref>\n\nHe became an Officer of the Order of the British Empire. He was ranked colonel of the [[Australian Army]] during [[World War I]] and had as post being finance member of the [[Australian Military Board]] in October 1920.<ref name=gaz32090>{{London Gazette|issue=32090|pages=10095\u201310098|date=19 October 1920}}</ref> He received the OBE (selected) Australian War Honour that year.<ref>[http://www.gazettes-online.co.uk/archiveViewFrameSetup.asp?webtype=0&IssueNumber=32090&PageDuplicate=n&pageNumber=19&SearchFor=graciously%20pleased&selMedalType=&selHonourType= (gazetted 19 October 1920; dated 15 October 1920)]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Wales international footballers (alphabetical)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Thomas Thomas\n|image          =\n| image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|fullname       =  Thomas John Thomas\n|birth_date     = 1877\n|birth_place    = Wales\n|death_date     = <!--{{death date and age|||||||df=yes}}-->\n|death_place    =\n|height         =\n|position       =\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    =\n|years1         =\n|clubs1         =\n|caps1          =\n|goals1         =\n|years2         =\n|clubs2         =\n|caps2          =\n|goals2         =\n|totalcaps      =\n|totalgoals     =\n|nationalyears1 = 1898\n|nationalteam1  = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  =\n| managerclubs1  =\n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Thomas John Thomas''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 1877) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] international [[association football|footballer]]. He was part of the [[Wales national football team]], playing 2 matches. He played his first match on 19 February 1898 against Ireland and his last match on 19 March 1898 against Scotland .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_players.php?id=218|title=Wales player database 1872 to 2013|publisher=eu-football.info|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe studied at the [[Friars School, Bangor]].<ref name=\"Bangor FC\">{{Cite web | url = http://homepages.tesco.net/~BCSA/History/Welshints.htm | title = Welsh International Caps | accessdate = 16 November 2008 | author = History of Bangor City Football Club website | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090203125130/http://homepages.tesco.net/~BCSA/History/Welshints.htm | archivedate = 3 February 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.iffhs.de/?29da15a85b1529d815a89ad5285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec28d6edb0ae1d | title = Welsh Cup 1895/96 | accessdate = 16 November 2008 | author = IFFHS}}</ref>\n\nHe became an Officer of the Order of the British Empire. He was ranked colonel of the [[Australian Army]] during [[World War I]] and had as post being finance member of the [[Australian Military Board]] in October 1920.<ref name=gaz32090>{{London Gazette|issue=32090|pages=10095\u201310098|date=19 October 1920}}</ref> He received the OBE (selected) Australian War Honour that year.<ref>[http://www.gazettes-online.co.uk/archiveViewFrameSetup.asp?webtype=0&IssueNumber=32090&PageDuplicate=n&pageNumber=19&SearchFor=graciously%20pleased&selMedalType=&selHonourType= (gazetted 19 October 1920; dated 15 October 1920)]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Wales international footballers (alphabetical)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Wales-footy-bio-